Question 1. Working with Customer Data with Health Insurance

Read the data file, custdata_rev.csv, as the data.frame object with the name, health_cust:

library(tidyverse)
library(skimr)

health_cust <- read_csv(
  'https://bcdanl.github.io/data/custdata_rev.csv'
)

Variable Description for health_cust

The following describes the variables in the health_cust data.frame.

  • custid: ID of customer
  • sex: Sex
  • is_employed: Employment status
    • NA: Unknown or not applicable
    • TRUE: Employed
    • FALSE: Unemployed
  • income: Income (in $)
  • marital_status: Marital status
  • housing_type: Housing type
  • recent_move:
    • TRUE: Recently moved
    • FALSE: Not recently moved
  • age: Age
  • state_of_res: State of residence
  • gas_usage: Gas usage
    • NA: Unknown or not applicable
    • 001: Included in rent or condo fee
    • 002: Included in electricity payment
    • 003: No charge or gas not used
    • 004-999: $4 to $999 (rounded and top-coded)
  • health_ins: Health insuarance status
    • TRUE: customer with health insuarance
    • FALSE: customer without health insuarance



Q1a

Report summary statistics including a mean value for each logical variable in health_cust.

Answer:

health_cust_sum <- skim(health_cust)

q1a <- health_cust_sum[health_cust_sum$skim_type == 'logical', 
                       c('skim_variable', 
                         'n_missing', 'complete_rate',
                         'logical.mean', 'logical.count')]


Q1b

Use health_cust data.frame to create a new data.frame, health_cust2, in which (1) age is greater than 0 and less than 100; and (2) income is positive.

Answer:

health_cust2 <- health_cust[health_cust$age > 0, ]
health_cust2 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$age < 100, ]
health_cust2 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$income > 0, ]
health_cust2_sum <- skim(health_cust2)

# Combining all conditions into one, which we will cover after the first midterm:
# health_cust2 <- health_cust[ ( 0 < health_cust$age < 100 ) &
#                                 ( health_cust$income > 0 ), ]


Q1c

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the distribution of income.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2, aes(x = income)) +
  geom_histogram()

ggplot(health_cust2, aes(x = income)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)

ggplot(health_cust2, aes(x = log(income))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100)

ggplot(health_cust2, aes(x = log(income))) +
  geom_freqpoly(bins = 100)

  • Provide some comments


Q1d

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the distribution of marital_status.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2,
       aes(y = marital_status,
           fill = marital_status)) +
  geom_bar(show.legend = F)

  • Provide some comments


Q1e

Suppose you randomly pick one customer’s observation from each state in data.frame health_cust.

Use ggplot code to find: (1) in which state a customer is most likely to have a health insurance; and (2) in which state a customer is least likely to have a health insurance.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins,
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(state_of_res ~ . , ncol = 5)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins, x = stat(prop),
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(state_of_res ~ . , ncol = 5)

  • The proportional bar chart faceted by state_of_res is the one we need.
    • Alaska customer is most likely to have health insurance.
    • Hawaii customer is least likely to have health insurance.
    • Why?

The following might mislead…

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = state_of_res, x = stat(prop),
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~ . , ncol = 5)


Q1f

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the relationship between age and income.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2, size = .75) +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

ggplot(health_cust2,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_hex() +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

# Considering income level below $250,000
health_cust3 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$income < 2.5*10^5, ]
ggplot(health_cust3,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_hex() +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

  • Considering the income group whose level is below $250,000, income is positively associated with age up to age around 55. income is then negatively associated from age around 55 to 100.


Q1g

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the relationship between age and health_ins.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age), bins = 75) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) + 
  geom_freqpoly(aes(x = age), bins = 75) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)


Q1h

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the relationship between marital_status and health_ins.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins))

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins),
           position = "fill")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins),
           position = "dodge")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_grid(marital_status ~.)


Q1i

Provide ggplot code and comments to describe the relationship between marital_status and housing_type.

Answer:

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = housing_type))

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = housing_type),
           position = "fill")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = housing_type),
           position = "dodge")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status)) +
  facet_wrap(housing_type ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(housing_type ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = housing_type, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_grid(marital_status ~.)

# Question 1. Working with Customer Data with Health Insurance

Read the data file, `custdata_rev.csv`, as the data.frame object with the name, `health_cust`:

```{r}
#| echo: true
library(tidyverse)
library(skimr)

health_cust <- read_csv(
  'https://bcdanl.github.io/data/custdata_rev.csv'
)
```

```{r}
#| results: asis
#| echo: false
rmarkdown::paged_table(health_cust)
```


## Variable Description for `health_cust`

The following describes the variables  in the `health_cust` data.frame.

- `custid`: ID of customer
- `sex`: Sex
- `is_employed`: Employment status
  - `NA`: Unknown or not applicable
  - `TRUE`: Employed
  - `FALSE`: Unemployed
- `income`: Income (in $)
- `marital_status`: Marital status
- `housing_type`: Housing type
- `recent_move`: 
  - `TRUE`: Recently moved
  - `FALSE`: Not recently moved
- `age`: Age
- `state_of_res`: State of residence
- `gas_usage`: Gas usage
  - `NA`: Unknown or not applicable
  - `001`: Included in rent or condo fee
  - `002`: Included in electricity payment
  - `003`: No charge or gas not used
  - `004`-`999`: $4 to $999 (rounded and top-coded)
- `health_ins`: Health insuarance status
  - `TRUE`: customer with health insuarance 
  - `FALSE`: customer without health insuarance

## Q1b 
Use `health_cust` data.frame to create a new data.frame, `health_cust2`, in which 
(1) `age` is greater than 0 and less than 100; and
(2) `income` is positive.

**Answer:**

```{r}
health_cust2 <- health_cust[health_cust$age > 0, ]
health_cust2 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$age < 100, ]
health_cust2 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$income > 0, ]
health_cust2_sum <- skim(health_cust2)

# Combining all conditions into one, which we will cover after the first midterm:
# health_cust2 <- health_cust[ ( 0 < health_cust$age < 100 ) &
#                                 ( health_cust$income > 0 ), ]

```

## Q1e 
Suppose you randomly pick one customer's observation 
from each state in data.frame `health_cust`.

Use ggplot code to find:
(1) in which state a customer is most likely to have a health insurance; and
(2) in which state a customer is least likely to have a health insurance.

**Answer:**

```{r, fig.width=12, fig.height=20}
ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins,
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(state_of_res ~ . , ncol = 5)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins, x = stat(prop),
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(state_of_res ~ . , ncol = 5)
```
- The proportional bar chart faceted by `state_of_res` is the one we need.
  - `Alaska` customer is most likely to have health insurance.
  - `Hawaii` customer is least likely to have health insurance.
  - Why? 


The following might mislead...
```{r, fig.width=12, fig.height=20}
ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = state_of_res, x = stat(prop),
               group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~ . , ncol = 5)

```

<br>





## Q1f 
Provide ggplot code and comments to describe 
the relationship between `age` and `income`.

**Answer:**

```{r}
ggplot(health_cust2,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2, size = .75) +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

ggplot(health_cust2,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_hex() +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

# Considering income level below $250,000
health_cust3 <- health_cust2[health_cust2$income < 2.5*10^5, ]
ggplot(health_cust3,
       aes(x = age, y = income)) +
  geom_hex() +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = 'red')

```

- Considering the income group whose level is below $250,000, `income` is positively associated with `age` up to `age` around 55. `income` is then negatively associated from age around 55 to 100.

<br>





## Q1g 
Provide ggplot code and comments to describe 
the relationship between `age` and `health_ins`.

**Answer:**

```{r}
ggplot(health_cust2) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age), bins = 75) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) + 
  geom_freqpoly(aes(x = age), bins = 75) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

```

<br>





## Q1h 
Provide ggplot code and comments to describe 
the relationship between `marital_status` and `health_ins`.

**Answer:**

```{r}
ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins))

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins),
           position = "fill")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               fill = health_ins),
           position = "dodge")

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = marital_status, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_wrap(health_ins ~.)

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = health_ins, 
               x = stat(prop), group = 1)) +
  facet_grid(marital_status ~.)

```

<br>

ggplot(health_cust2) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = housing_type,
